WEBVTT

00:00.467 --> 00:03.068
<i>My name is Michael Westen.</i>
<i>I used to be a spy until...</i>

00:04.540 --> 00:07.041
We got a burn notice
on you. You're blacklisted.

00:07.640 --> 00:09.810
<i>When you're burned,</i>
<i>you've got nothing --</i>

00:09.934 --> 00:12.330
<i>no cash, no credit,</i>
<i>no job history.</i>

00:12.453 --> 00:14.746
<i>You're stuck in whatever city</i>
<i>they decide to dump you in.</i>

00:14.914 --> 00:16.128
- Where am I?
- Miami.

00:16.226 --> 00:18.765
<i>You do whatever work</i>
<i>comes your way.</i>

00:19.374 --> 00:20.708
<i>You rely on anyone</i>
<i>who's still talking to you.</i>

00:21.650 --> 00:24.152
A trigger-happy ex-girlfriend --

00:24.220 --> 00:25.554
Should we shoot them?

00:25.623 --> 00:27.261
-- An old friend who used to

00:27.330 --> 00:28.965
inform on you to the FBI --

00:29.034 --> 00:30.133
You know spies --

00:30.201 --> 00:31.233
a bunch of bitchy little girls.

00:31.302 --> 00:31.834
-- Family, too --

00:31.903 --> 00:32.969
Hey, is that your mom again?

00:33.037 --> 00:33.805
-- If you're desperate.

00:33.874 --> 00:35.542
Someone needs your
help, Michael.

00:35.611 --> 00:36.643
Bottom line --

00:36.712 --> 00:38.081
as long as you're burned, you're

00:38.149 --> 00:40.292
not going anywhere.

00:43.557 --> 00:44.957
As a field operative, some

00:45.025 --> 00:46.623
aspects of life aren't part of

00:46.692 --> 00:48.866
your daily experience.

00:48.901 --> 00:49.983
You may be familiar with the

00:49.984 --> 00:51.634
mountains of Afghanistan or know

00:51.635 --> 00:52.908
how to break down a .50-caliber

00:52.909 --> 00:55.466
machine gun, but that expertise

00:55.467 --> 00:56.800
comes at the cost of certain

00:56.869 --> 00:59.517
normal activities people
take for granted.

00:59.518 --> 01:01.093
Keeping up with sports teams,

01:01.094 --> 01:03.502
for example, or the details of
lawn care --

01:04.885 --> 01:06.083
-- Or dealing with babies.

01:08.606 --> 01:10.903
You're sure it doesn't need
medical attention?

01:11.215 --> 01:12.652
Its name is Charlie.

01:12.653 --> 01:13.944
And your nephew's fine, bro.

01:13.945 --> 01:15.187
He just needs a little nap.

01:15.428 --> 01:17.148
Oh, by the way, mom --
thank you so much for the

01:17.163 --> 01:18.229
"welcome home" meat loaf.

01:18.298 --> 01:20.563
It was really -- it was
thoroughly cooked.

01:20.632 --> 01:23.705
And, uh, Ruth's going to be
bummed she missed it.

01:24.800 --> 01:26.878
Well, it's not every day you
can get a pedicure.

01:28.624 --> 01:29.423
So, how's Fiona?

01:29.492 --> 01:32.511
Mom told me you guys
are living together?

01:32.836 --> 01:34.169
Yes, we are.

01:34.237 --> 01:35.704
It's moving fast.

01:35.705 --> 01:38.271
At this rate, they
should be married by 60.

01:39.144 --> 01:39.943
Thanks for the food, mom.

01:40.012 --> 01:41.311
I'm going to go fix the Charger.

01:43.322 --> 01:44.941
Michael, is there going to be
an end to this?

01:45.150 --> 01:46.439
'Cause I want my garage back.

01:47.648 --> 01:50.885
Mom?

01:50.886 --> 01:52.869
Could you just support his head?

01:53.572 --> 01:54.204
You know, I mean, his little

01:54.273 --> 01:56.507
neck muscles are not
really developed yet.

01:57.543 --> 01:59.930
You may recall that I've done
this a couple of times.

02:01.673 --> 02:02.974
Anything else?

02:03.284 --> 02:05.194
No.
That's it.

02:12.200 --> 02:13.566
Hey, you know what
I was thinking?

02:13.635 --> 02:17.269
This would be an awesome
project for us.

02:17.338 --> 02:19.237
We could finally convert your

02:19.306 --> 02:21.807
ride into a spymobile.

02:21.875 --> 02:23.508
We'd put a smoke-screen button

02:23.577 --> 02:25.510
right here for
high-speed pursuits.

02:25.578 --> 02:26.344
You know what happens to

02:26.413 --> 02:27.211
smoke at 60 miles an hour?

02:27.280 --> 02:28.946
It dissipates.

02:29.015 --> 02:30.348
You doing all right, bro?

02:30.417 --> 02:32.699
Nate, why'd you
move back to Miami?

02:33.854 --> 02:34.619
See?

02:35.522 --> 02:36.799
Why do you got to be like that?

02:36.800 --> 02:38.328
It's important to me and Ruth

02:38.329 --> 02:39.763
that Charlie grow
up around family.

02:40.055 --> 02:41.995
The same Ruth who skipped the

02:41.996 --> 02:44.161
"welcome home" lunch
for a pedicure?

02:47.502 --> 02:48.568
Look, you know Vegas isn't

02:48.637 --> 02:50.871
the right kind of place for me.

02:50.939 --> 02:52.305
And since Charlie's been born,

02:52.374 --> 02:54.103
I've been trying to
keep my nose clean.

02:54.268 --> 02:56.436
I've been going back
to Gamblers Anonymous.

02:56.672 --> 02:57.615
Good for you.

02:57.879 --> 02:58.948
Yeah.

02:59.482 --> 03:00.622
It is good for me.

03:00.948 --> 03:02.777
But I-I was kind of hoping that

03:02.778 --> 03:05.414
you and mom could help me stay

03:05.415 --> 03:09.617
straight, 'cause, um,
family helps, bro.

03:10.260 --> 03:12.912
You can help with the Charger.

03:14.713 --> 03:15.712
Thanks.

03:15.915 --> 03:16.714
It's good to have you home.

03:18.800 --> 03:19.332
I should run.

03:19.401 --> 03:20.433
Yeah?

03:20.502 --> 03:22.108
Super-secret spy meeting?

03:22.226 --> 03:23.350
Super-secret.

03:24.073 --> 03:25.858
Oh.

03:32.878 --> 03:33.943
Fi, uh, I thought we were

03:34.012 --> 03:35.945
shopping for drapes.

03:36.014 --> 03:36.546
That store sells drapes.

03:36.615 --> 03:37.914
First things first.

03:37.983 --> 03:39.049
I'm buying you a paper shredder.

03:39.589 --> 03:40.394
Paper shredder?

03:40.494 --> 03:41.991
You seem preoccupied lately.

03:42.220 --> 03:42.852
I don't think it's healthy to

03:42.920 --> 03:44.599
keep files on the people who
ruined your life.

03:44.938 --> 03:47.727
Vaughn, Carla, management --

03:47.728 --> 03:49.888
they don't deserve a place in
your head or your file cabinet.

03:50.174 --> 03:52.474
I don't think some old files
are the problem, Fi.

03:52.690 --> 03:54.389
Well, let's get rid of them and see.

03:54.697 --> 03:56.363
That part of your life is over.

03:58.908 --> 03:59.925
Michael?

03:59.926 --> 04:01.606
I think we're being tailed.

04:01.607 --> 04:02.973
Man with the blue shopping bag.

04:03.830 --> 04:05.276
You sure?

04:05.277 --> 04:06.376
Not yet.

04:07.428 --> 04:08.494
I clocked him in the parking lot

04:08.563 --> 04:10.186
and the coffee place.

04:10.455 --> 04:11.888
I don't think it's
anything, Michael.

04:11.956 --> 04:13.737
- Let's split up and see.
- Fine.

04:15.319 --> 04:18.422
One of the toughest parts of
adjusting to civilian life after

04:18.423 --> 04:20.755
a major operation
is the paranoia.

04:20.825 --> 04:21.624
You can't turn it off.

04:21.692 --> 04:25.934
If a shopper behind you is
carrying a suspicious package

04:25.935 --> 04:28.435
and avoiding eye contact, they

04:28.504 --> 04:29.569
could be there to do you harm.

04:29.638 --> 04:30.971
And if you're right about the

04:31.040 --> 04:34.019
threat, the consequences
could be serious.

04:35.736 --> 04:37.380
What do you want?
What do you want?!

04:37.521 --> 04:38.851
Daddy?

04:38.852 --> 04:40.602
Of course, if you're wrong,

04:40.603 --> 04:42.803
the consequences could
be serious, as well.

04:42.804 --> 04:44.183
Michael!

04:44.184 --> 04:44.683
I'm sorry.

04:44.751 --> 04:45.851
I thought I --
What are you doing?

04:46.404 --> 04:48.037
I thought that -- I-I'm sorry.
My -- my boyfriend is --

04:48.173 --> 04:51.001
Your boyfriend is
a psycho, lady.

04:51.210 --> 04:53.172
Come on, honey.

04:59.069 --> 05:02.655
Post-operation paranoia isn't
something you can control.

05:02.888 --> 05:03.953
It's with you always --

05:04.443 --> 05:06.377
when you're working,
when you're relaxing.

05:06.445 --> 05:09.603
Even sleep is no escape.

05:17.693 --> 05:18.971
There's nothing there.

05:21.185 --> 05:22.223
You're dreaming again.

05:23.899 --> 05:25.443
We took care of it.

05:27.073 --> 05:28.691
Okay?

05:33.169 --> 05:36.169
<font color=#00FF00>Burn Notice 5x03</font>
<font color=#00FFFF>Mind Games</font>
